window.docContents[241].resolve({"/Analytic-Number-Theory/The-Selberg-sieve/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Analytic-Number-Theory--The-Selberg-sieve--The-Selberg-sieve":{"contents":"A Selberg sieve packages the data needed to bound, from above, the number of elements of a finite\nweighted sequence that survive sifting by a set of primes. In mathlib a SelbergSieve extends a\nBoundingSieve: a finite support with non-negative weights, a squarefree product of sifting primes\nprodPrimes, a multiplicative density  with  on the sifting primes, a total\nmass totalMass, and a real level . The sifted sum\n\n() counts the weight of the unsifted elements, and the remainders\n measure the failure of the density\nmodel.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Analytic Number Theory\u0009The Selberg sieve","header":"2.6.1. The Selberg sieve","id":"/Analytic-Number-Theory/The-Selberg-sieve/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Analytic-Number-Theory--The-Selberg-sieve--The-Selberg-sieve"},"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Dirichlet___s-approximation-theorem-and-Legendre___s-converse/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Dirichlet___s-approximation-theorem-and-Legendre___s-converse--Infinitely-Many-Good-Rational-Approximations":{"contents":"(Infinitely many good approximations.) An irrational real number  has infinitely many\nrational approximations  (in lowest terms) with\n\n\nIterating Dirichlet's theorem produces, from any rational approximation , a strictly better one\n with  and \n(exists_rat_abs_sub_lt_and_lt_of_irrational): choose  and apply\n in its denominator-bounded form ( uses\nReal.exists_rat_abs_sub_le_and_den_le), whose output beats  because  is irrational, hence\n. Since each good approximation can be strictly improved, no finite set of them can be\nexhaustive, so infinitely many exist. This is the infinitude that drives the existence of nontrivial\nPell solutions.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Diophantine Equations and Transcendence\u0009Dirichlet's approximation theorem and Legendre's converse","header":"9.3.2. Infinitely Many Good Rational Approximations","id":"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Dirichlet___s-approximation-theorem-and-Legendre___s-converse/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Dirichlet___s-approximation-theorem-and-Legendre___s-converse--Infinitely-Many-Good-Rational-Approximations"},"/Elementary-Number-Theory/Fermat-and-Mersenne-numbers/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Elementary-Number-Theory--Fermat-and-Mersenne-numbers--Fermat-Numbers-and-Their-Coprimality":{"contents":"The Fermat numbers are . Distinct Fermat numbers are coprime:\n\n\nThe recurrence  is proved by induction. Hence if , then , so any common divisor  of  and  divides ; but every Fermat number is odd, so . (Coprimality of the  gives, as a corollary, another proof of the infinitude of primes, : a fresh prime divides each . The argument that a common divisor reduces to a divisor of  uses divisibility in the style of .)\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Elementary Number Theory\u0009Fermat and Mersenne numbers","header":"1.6.1. Fermat Numbers and Their Coprimality","id":"/Elementary-Number-Theory/Fermat-and-Mersenne-numbers/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Elementary-Number-Theory--Fermat-and-Mersenne-numbers--Fermat-Numbers-and-Their-Coprimality"}});